vectorData.altText: That's right!  The ventrolateral sulcus (I) subdivides the white matter of the spinal cord into ventral and lateral columns.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

You will recall from your neurohistology eModule that white matter is neural tissue rich in axons and oligodendrocytes and grey matter is neural tissue rich in neuronal cell bodies and astrocytes.
In the spinal cord, white matter is superficial and grey matter is deep. The spinal cord white matter consists largely of axons that carry sensory information upward, and motor information downward. 
Longitudinal grooves subdivide the spinal cord white matter. 
The ventral median fissure and dorsal median sulcus separate the spinal cord white matter into right and left sides    . 
The dorsolateral and ventrolateral sulci subdivide the spinal cord white matter into the ventral, lateral and dorsal columns.
Some grooves on the surface of the brain and spinal cord are called fissures, while others are called sulci. Fissures are deeper and wider than sulci.
